DDI Data Visualisation in RStudio

As an introduction to applied data visualisation we are going to generate some plots from an existing dataset in RStudio. I will show you how to do the following things in this exercise:

  • Install & load the RStudio packages
  • Create a bar plot from the Diamonds dataset
  • Add layers to the plot to make it more informative
  • Adjust the aesthetic features of the plot

NOTE Try not copy & paste code from this doc; typing out the code is essential to developing your programming skills!

A little introduction

The following block of code will install and load RStudio’s Tidyverse package. The Tidyverse is a suit of functions and datasets that allow you to create simple and interpretable code for tidying, wrangling, visualising and analysing data. Here, we are going to play with some of the visualising commmands of the ggplot2 package that is loaded with the Tidyverse.

Getting Started

To get started create a new project in RStudio and save to a meaningful location. Once installed, open a new script (Ctrl + Shift + N) and enter the following code:

# Install packages

install.packages('tidyverse') # install the tidyverse package
install.packages('RColorBrewer') # install colour brewer
install.packages('plotly') # install plotly for interactive visualisations

Do not be concerned by RStudio’s request to store packages in a local library. This is so you can use these packages in future without the need to install. You may also see several warning messages about the package version or conflicts. You can ignore these so long as the package is successfully installed.

After a package is installed is must be loaded into RStudio for use.

# Load packages

library(tidyverse) # load the tidyverse
library(RColorBrewer) # load colour brewer
library(plotly)

I want to say a little about commenting here. Using the # key allows you to add inactive text to your script. So, you can add comments using # to keep a log of your activity

Running the code

To run the code hit Ctrl + ENTER. You can peform this action on multiple lines by highlighting them. Text will appear in the console section. This is fine, RStudio is just installing the package dependencies. Save the script (Ctrl + S) as ddi-vis.

Download the data

The diamonds data is part of the Tidyverse library. So, we can load it into our workspace using a few simple commands

data <-    # this is the assign symbol
  diamonds # we have assigned the existing dataset 'diamonds' to our dataframe 'data'

The Diamonds Dataset

Here is the official Diamonds dataset webpage. Diamonds is a data frame with 53940 rows and 10 variables. Here’s information about the variables in the data:

  • price = price in US dollars ($326–$18,823)
  • carat = weight of the diamond (0.2–5.01)
  • cut = quality of the cut (Fair, Good, Very Good, Premium, Ideal)
  • color = diamond colour, from D (best) to J (worst)
  • clarity = a measurement of how clear the diamond is (I1 (worst), SI2, SI1, VS2, VS1, VVS2, VVS1, IF (best))
  • x = length in mm (0–10.74)
  • y = width in mm (0–58.9)
  • z = depth in mm (0–31.8)
  • depth = total depth percentage = z / mean(x, y) = 2 * z / (x + y) (43–79)
  • table = width of top of diamond relative to widest point (43–95)

Examining the data

We can take a quick look at the data by clicking the data object that has been created in the Global Environment or by using the following code

View(data) # opens a new tab with a large subset of the dataset

glimpse(data) # gives a summary of the data variables

head(data) # top 6 rows

tail(data) # final 6 rows

dim(data) # dimensions of the data object

As the dataset is quite large with several variables it’s difficult to glean any trends just by observing the raw data. This is where the power of data visualisation really comes to the fore.

Visualising the Diamonds Dataset

Let’s start by plotting the frequency of the different cut qualities.

Plot of Cut Quality Frequency

Add a comment using # to state what you are about to do. Then enter the following code.

ggplot(data) +          # call ggplot2, use data dataframe "data" 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut)) # set `cut` as our x-axis variable

This plot is useful in that we can see which of the cuts is most frequent in the dataset. Most of the diamonds are an “ideal” cut. However, it is not very informative (as it only covers one variable) nor aesthetically pleasing. In a good plot the key information should pop out at you.

Adding Colour

One way to make you plot pop is with colour.

ggplot(data) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = cut)) # set the bar fill to `cut` variable

Here we get a much clearer distinction between the different cuts.

Adding another variable

We can augment this plot with information about the diamonds clarity.

ggplot(data) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = clarity)) # set the bar fill to `clarity`

Have a look at the variables summary above. In the variable clarity I1 = low clarity; IF = high clarity. So, you can begin to appreciate how good data visualization tells a detailed story about the data.

Adjusting the Aesthetics: Transparency

As clarity is present as a variable, you may wish to adjust the bars transparency for thematic effect.

ggplot(data, mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = clarity)) + 
  geom_bar(alpha = 1/5,   # set the alpha transparency level to 1/5
           position = "identity") # use the raw data values

Going too far

It’s easy to overcook things when playing with the aesthetics. This is what the plot looks like if you remove the fill colouring.

ggplot(data, mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = clarity)) + 
  geom_bar(fill = NA, position = "identity")

Changing Barplot Type

We can stack the variables cut and clarity to present proportions in a single bar using the argument position = "fill".

ggplot(data) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = clarity), position = "fill") 

# `position = "fill"` tells ggplot to stack by `clarity` categories

So, the y-axis now represents the proportion of the dataset (e.g., from 0-1). Whether or not this is easier to interpret is subjective.

You can also try stacking the bars side by side using position = "dodge"

ggplot(data) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = clarity), position = "dodge") 

# `position = "dodge"` tells ggplot to side-stack by `clarity` units

Tidying Up Other Elements

Plot Theme

The plot theme is another important aesthetic feature. There are several existing themes in the ggplot2 library.

# classic

ggplot(data) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = clarity)) +
  theme_classic()

# minimal

ggplot(data) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = clarity)) +
  theme_minimal()

# dark

ggplot(data) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = clarity)) +
  theme_dark()

Create Theme to Standardise Plot Aesthetic

ggplot axis label text size quite small by default We can edit this using the theme command

# create your own theme

my_theme <-
  theme_classic(base_size = 15) + # change the base size of text
  theme(
    axis.title = element_text(size = rel(1.05)), # adjust the relative size of axis text
    legend.title = element_text(size = rel(1.05)), # adjust the relative size of the legend text
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))  # centre the title (Horizontal alignment: 0 = left, 0.5 = center, 1 = right)

# apply theme to a plot

ggplot(data) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = clarity)) +
  ggtitle("Cut and Clarity of Diamonds") +
  my_theme

Axis labels can be modified using the labs command.

# labels can be amended with the `labs` argument

ggplot(data) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = clarity)) +
  ggtitle("Cut and Clarity of Diamonds") +
  labs(x = "\nCut", y = "Frequency\n") +
  my_theme

Notice the use of the newline \n command to space out the axis labels better.

Examples of other plot types

I have given you the tools for building tidy bar-plots. However, there are many other types of plot. Let’s stick to the diamonds dataset and try some others for fun.

Jitter Plot of Diamonds Cut and Clarity

ggplot(data, aes(cut, y = clarity)) + 
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.05) +
  labs(title = "Diamond Frequency by Cut and Clarity", 
       x = "\nCut", 
       y = "Clarity\n") +
  my_theme

geom_jitter generates a dotplot that “jitters” the points by adding statistical noise. This makes it easier to compare counts between all combinations of two variables (in our case cut and clarity).

Diamond data Boxplots

Boxplots can also be used to examine the relationship between the diamonds price cut and quality. As this plot will include 3 variables it can be said to be multivariate.

I’ve assigned the plot to an object first to apply a new colour scheme with the RColourBrewer package.

bp <-
  data %>%
  dplyr::filter(cut %in% c("Premium", "Ideal")) %>% # let's take a look at Premium and Ideal cuts spcifically
  ggplot(., aes(factor(cut), price, fill=clarity)) + 
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) + # do not plot outliers
  ggtitle("Diamond Price According to Cut and Clarity\n") + 
  labs(x = "Cut\n", y = "\nDiamond Price US$") +
  ylim(0,7500) +
  coord_flip() # flip the plot 90 degrees clockwise
  
  

bp + 
  my_theme +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette="Set2") +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(title = "Clarity", # rename the legend
                             reverse = TRUE)) # reverse the order of the legend items

The bold lines on the box represent the median, and the ‘whiskers’ are the minimum and maximum.

Plotting Relationships using Facet

bf <-
  data %>%
  dplyr::filter(cut %in% c("Premium", "Ideal"),
                color %in% c("D", "E", "J")) %>% # let's take a look at Premium and Ideal cuts spcifically
  ggplot(., aes(factor(cut), price, fill=clarity)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  ggtitle("Diamond Price According to Colour, Clarity and Cut\n") + 
  labs(x = "Cut\n", y = "\nDiamond Price U$") + 
  ylim(0,7500) +
  coord_flip() + # flip the plot 90 degrees clockwise
  facet_grid(cols = vars(color))
  

bf +
  my_theme +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette="Set2") +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(title = "Clarity", 
                             reverse = TRUE)) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust = 1, vjust = 1)) # adjust x-axis text angle

Creating an Interactive Plot using plotly

The plotly package allows us to add levels of interactivity to our visualisations such as subsetting displays by selecting variable levels.

bp <-
  ggplot(data) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = clarity)) +
  ggtitle("Cut and Clarity of Diamonds") +
  labs(x = "\nCut", y = "Frequency\n") +
  my_theme

ggplotly(bp) # create interactve version of plot

  • Today, I’ve scratched the surface of what is possible, and hopefully whet your data vis appetites!
